@startuml engineering-environment-context-map

title Map the Engineering Environment Before Optimizing the Agent
caption Start with the software engineering process, then make the context required at each stage accessible from the working environment.

left to right direction
scale max 2600 width

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam roundCorner 12
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 13
skinparam ArrowColor #526170
skinparam ArrowThickness 1
skinparam packageStyle rectangle
skinparam packageBorderColor #71808F
skinparam packageFontColor #263442
skinparam rectangleBorderColor #71808F
skinparam rectangleFontColor #263442
skinparam noteBorderColor #B68424
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #FFF7D6

actor "Human or agent" as worker
rectangle "Work\nFeature · fix · maintenance\nincident · investigation" as work #E8F1FA

package "Software engineering process" as process #F7F9FB {
  rectangle "<b>1. Understand</b>\nWhy does this matter?\nWhat exists today?" as understand #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>2. Define</b>\nWhat must change?\nWhere are the boundaries?" as define #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>3. Design</b>\nHow should it work?\nWhat are the trade-offs?" as design #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>4. Implement</b>\nMake the change in the\nworking environment" as implement #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>5. Validate & review</b>\nIs it correct, safe, usable\nand maintainable?" as validate #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>6. Deliver</b>\nIntegrate, migrate, release\nand deploy safely" as deliver #DCEEFF
  rectangle "<b>7. Operate & learn</b>\nObserve real behaviour\nand feed learning back" as operate #DCEEFF

  understand -right-> define
  define -right-> design
  design -right-> implement
  implement -right-> validate
  validate -right-> deliver
  deliver -right-> operate
  operate .left.> understand : learning
}

worker --> work
work --> understand

package "Possible context required at each stage" as mapped_context #F4FAF4 {
  rectangle "<b>Understand</b>\n• user and stakeholder needs\n• strategy, goals and desired outcomes\n• product and domain model\n• current behaviour and known limitations\n• architecture and change history\n• usage, support and production evidence" as c_understand #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Define</b>\n• problem and intended outcome\n• scope and non-goals\n• acceptance and success criteria\n• priority, dependencies and constraints\n• risks, assumptions and open questions\n• owner and decision authority" as c_define #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Design</b>\n• architectural principles and boundaries\n• data, API and integration contracts\n• security, privacy and compliance\n• performance, reliability and accessibility\n• compatibility, migration and rollout\n• alternatives, rationale and trade-offs" as c_design #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Implement</b>\n• repository structure and conventions\n• source, configuration and dependencies\n• types, schemas, APIs and examples\n• templates, generators and migrations\n• setup, commands, tools and permissions\n• current task, workspace and environment state" as c_implement #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Validate & review</b>\n• acceptance criteria and expected behaviour\n• tests, fixtures and representative data\n• static analysis, builds and CI\n• quality, security and compliance checks\n• reviewers, ownership and approval policy\n• evidence required and practical quality bar" as c_validate #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Deliver</b>\n• branch, version and release policy\n• environments and live platform state\n• deployment and migration procedures\n• feature flags, approvals and communication\n• compatibility and dependency coordination\n• rollback, recovery and support readiness" as c_deliver #E2F3E5

  rectangle "<b>Operate & learn</b>\n• outcomes, usage and customer feedback\n• SLOs, telemetry, dashboards and alerts\n• runbooks, ownership and on-call paths\n• incidents, defects and support history\n• security, cost, capacity and reliability\n• lessons that should change future work" as c_operate #E2F3E5

  c_understand -[hidden]right-> c_define
  c_define -[hidden]right-> c_design
  c_design -[hidden]right-> c_implement
  c_implement -[hidden]right-> c_validate
  c_validate -[hidden]right-> c_deliver
  c_deliver -[hidden]right-> c_operate
}

understand -down-> c_understand : needs
define -down-> c_define : needs
design -down-> c_design : needs
implement -down-> c_implement : needs
validate -down-> c_validate : needs
deliver -down-> c_deliver : needs
operate -down-> c_operate : needs

package "How that context should be made available" as availability #FAF7FC {
  rectangle "<b>Task-specific</b>\nPrompt, issue or work item\nClarifications and decisions\nCurrent plan and progress\nPrevious attempts and failures\n\n<i>Keep with the task; do not turn\nevery detail into repository guidance.</i>" as task_context #EEE3F5

  rectangle "<b>Durable repository context</b>\nREADME and AGENTS.md routing\nDocumentation, glossary and ADRs\nCode, configuration and history\nTypes, schemas, APIs and examples\nScripts, templates, tests, CI and runbooks\n\n<i>Encode stable local knowledge and\nenforce constraints where possible.</i>" as repository_context #EEE3F5

  rectangle "<b>External authoritative context</b>\nProduct, research and design systems\nIssue trackers and service catalogues\nOrganisation, legal and security policies\nPlatform and dependency documentation\n\n<i>Link or retrieve it from the repository;\ndo not maintain a conflicting copy.</i>" as external_context #EEE3F5

  rectangle "<b>Transient and live context</b>\nBranch, worktree and uncommitted changes\nInstalled dependencies and active processes\nTools, permissions, network and runtime\nDeployments, flags, metrics, logs and incidents\n\n<i>Inspect or query it when the task runs;\ndo not persist accidental state.</i>" as live_context #DDF1F1

  rectangle "<b>Controlled context</b>\nSecrets and credentials\nPersonal or customer data\nPrivate vulnerabilities\nPrivileged systems and operations\n\n<i>Provide authorised, auditable access\nwithout copying sensitive values.</i>" as controlled_context #F7E3E3

  rectangle "<b>Implicit and human context</b>\nTacit domain knowledge and rationale\nUnwritten norms and intended patterns\nInformal ownership and decision rights\nWorkarounds, incentives and risk tolerance\n\n<i>Clarify when needed; make stable and\nrecurring knowledge explicit.</i>" as implicit_context #FFF0BD

  task_context -[hidden]right-> repository_context
  repository_context -[hidden]right-> external_context
  external_context -[hidden]right-> live_context
  live_context -[hidden]right-> controlled_context
  controlled_context -[hidden]right-> implicit_context
}

c_understand -[hidden]down-> task_context

note bottom of availability
  The repository is the working interface, not necessarily the source of every fact.
  It should contain durable local context and clearly route people and agents to
  task-specific, external, live, controlled and human sources when they are authoritative.

  Missing, unclear, stale or contradictory context encountered at any stage becomes
  evidence for the engineering-environment feedback loop explored in the following post.
end note

legend right
  |= Colour |= Meaning |
  |<#DCEEFF> | Engineering process |
  |<#E2F3E5> | Context mapped to a process stage |
  |<#EEE3F5> | Durable or authoritative context source |
  |<#DDF1F1> | Task-time and live state |
  |<#F7E3E3> | Access-controlled context |
  |<#FFF0BD> | Implicit or tacit context |
endlegend

@enduml
